//A shudder rang across all that was living. The instinctual understanding that life shall be no more. The end wasn't an explosion or some fantastical nuclear warfare.//
//It was silent... and so, so bright.//

[Clink]

It didn't happen immediately. Instead, it was approximately 7 minutes after the fact. It was a countdown that no one could hear. One by one Foundation satellites loses communication with Earth.

One by one it got closer and closer. The bright light that enveloped the world. No one noticed until it was too late.


[Clink]

Number 39.
I was on the basement level of Site-18 when it happened. I was finishing up some paperwork, for retirement. I was also talking to my wife, for some company... God, I miss her voice. Midway through our talk though... our phones disconnected.

I tried calling back but my phone wouldn't even start ringing. I thought it was just crappy service. Then the lights shut off, leaving me in the darkness of my office for about ten seconds. 

They came back on but the phone still wasn't working. I thought it was just crappy service and bad electricity, so I decided to get back to the paperwork, but my computer couldn't even connect to the internet.
 
I left my office and made my way to the exit door so I could gather some of the technicians. At the door, I saw one of the guards, his name was Logan Smith. 

"Do you know what's going on out there?" I asked. "Trying to get some paperwork done. Are any of the technicians out." 

