//I said I was making a pit stop for supplies. Checking for any canned food...but I'm pretty sure he understood my real reasons. I just had to check... I already knew but I just had to see it. I just had to see it with my own eyes... and there you were. Your ashes still grasping the phone. I'm sorry Monika... I should've been there with you.//

[Clink]

Number 77
The ride was as smooth as one would think. It was still so quiet, with the only noise coming from our own engine. No road rage, no excessive and prudent honking, nobody trying to sell us flowers at a red light. I hated every second of it.

We ended up passing through a gated community, just to check if there was anything we could find useful for the rest of the ride. Meat, water... beer. It took us an hour to find something that wasn't completely covered in ash. 

[Clink]

Logan was already back at the truck waiting for me. I decided to check one more house for a beer before heading back. Then I heard something behind me.

It was Logan crouching silently behind me, motioning for me to get down. I asked him, "what's the problem." He said nothing but prompted me to look through the kitchen window.

At first, I thought it was a naked man simply covered in ash, but no... that was no man. Covered, no, made of ash, it was tall, I'm guessing two-hundred and thirty centimeters. Its body was shaped like the human muscular system. 

But it had no mouth, bearing its teeth, and its hands had no fingers, instead sharpened and long knife-like structures, and it held no eyes, but rather deep sockets filled with a void except for the tiny white dot you could find inside.

[Clink]

Logan whispered, "it spooked me and I ran off. I don't think it can hear us but I don't know about its sight. We need to get back to the car, now."

That was the plan... the only plan we had in mind. There was no telling how many there were out there. We began silently exiting the house, watching our every step, making sure not to slip.

As we made our way through each house and intersection, more and more of those things popped up. It felt like it was getting denser and denser the closer we got to the truck. I thought by the time we made it, we would have already lost a few limbs. But then, involuntary bait appeared.

A kid, no older than fifteen, was walking the opposite way from our truck. He was covered up, with a mask on for the ash. To survive as long as he did was nothing short of a miracle. A miracle... that miracle failed him.

[Clink]

He took one wrong step and came into view of one of those things. It was like the air froze and things became even more silent. Simultaneously, they turned their heads toward the boy's direction, as if they all say through the single walking ash.

Then... then they all charged the boy. We took the opportunity and ran to the truck but I foolishly looked backward. He was being ripped apart. They ripped his limbs from his body and shredded them finely enough to where the fragments of bones blended in nicely with the ash. 

They pulled his intestines through every pore of his body like an amateur playing with a yarn ball. His screaming was guttural, you could hear him fighting the blood rushing throughout his throat until they relieved him of his esophagus. 

They pulled his spine out, tore his jaw off, and smashed his head until it was just jelly. The boy was no longer a boy but instead, a meaty slop left for nothing to devour at this stage in the world. It felt too disrespectful... 

[Clink]

We made it to the car and didn't talk about what had transpired for the rest of the ride. It was a mutual understanding that there was nothing we could do. That's a lie...

[Clink]

We could've taken a gamble. Diverted their attention or something.

[Silence]

That's a lie...

[Clink]

