Number 99
We arrived at the vicinity surrounding the Site. We were expecting more sound but the deafening silence was as potent as ever. Logan, now on the passenger's side, looked for any survivors in this sea of ash.

But no one showed themselves. At this point, we were starting to become even more anxious. Was the signal something set up before everybody died? Is there really something that can reverse all this? 

[Clink]

While surfing through this sea of thoughts. Logan pointed something out to me. Blood. We passed a faint trail of blood. From what we understood, this world-ending anomaly didn't cause anyone to bleed. But we knew what did. 

Down the field, near the entranceway of Site 83, we noticed something. It was one of those things... the killing made from ash and at that moment... it noticed us.

It began running at speeds I couldn't conceive. I floored it trying to get past him so that we could make it inside the facility but then one of those things rose from the ash beneath us and sent our truck flying. 

[Clink]

Logan was the first one to regain his composure. He got out of the truck and pulled me out of it now that it was inoperable. We saw both charging at us, noticing our momentary weakness. Logan pulled out his rifle and fired at both.

They tripped and tumbled, the rifle slowed them down and damaged them but they were repairing themselves using the ash around them. He grabbed me by the arm, telling me we had to move but he didn't see what I saw. 

One of them formed themselves right behind him. I pushed him out the way before it swiped and instead of it knocking his head off, it took my eyes. From now on, I am forever in the dark.

I heard a shot echo. I felt a touch on my arm. I was lifted and carried, all the while the shots rang. I heard the cries of a man telling me to keep moving... to keep going. I could smell the ash, the metallic sting of my blood, and the intoxicating scent of gunpowder.

[Clink]

Right when I regained my bearings, I heard the stomps of an army trying to eradicate us. Then a push and then an order, run... forward.

The screams as I ran were gut-wrenching. I wish they took my ears instead. I ran into the facility, laptop in hand, unaware of my surroundings. Yet... I knew when to turn. When to go down the flight of stairs and then off.

[Clink]

Something was pulling me... and I knew what. 

[Clink]

I pushed for you to be suspended. I pushed for you to be thrown away...and I failed. I failed everyone. 

[Clink]

It pushed its little tendrils in every crevice it could possibly think of. I should've pushed harder.

[Andrew's breathing stutters with an on and off hiccup caused by the tears flowing down his face]

I think you understand now... and you probably felt its pull too. There's enough food and water to last you for weeks. Flip the coin... over and over and over. Until everything goes blank and this is all a dream.  I've flipped for so long and yet... I don't think anything changed.

I no longer have the strength to talk. My mind is numb and is now losing its hold. All I can do now...

[Clink]

[Clink]

Oh Monika...

[Clink]

